    <section class="guide-body">

      <p>
        The difference between a business that sells for the upper quartile of its industry multiple
        and one that sells for the lower quartile is rarely luck or timing. It is preparation.
        The factors that drive multiples higher - and the adjustments in the
        <a href="/">valuation calculator</a> - are almost entirely within a seller's control,
        given enough lead time.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide focuses on the specific actions with the highest measurable ROI, based on
        the adjustment factors reflected in {{ site.transactionCount }}+ closed transaction records.
      </p>

      <h2>1. Reduce Owner Involvement - the Highest-Leverage Action</h2>
      <p>
        The valuation calculator applies a ±0.20× multiple adjustment for owner involvement.
        On a business with $300,000 SDE and a 3.0× industry median, moving from high to low owner
        involvement shifts the multiple from 2.8× to 3.2× - a $120,000 valuation difference.
        No other single action available to most sellers produces a comparable dollar return.
      </p>
      <p>
        What "low owner involvement" means to buyers and lenders: the business generates its earnings
        through documented systems, trained staff, and accountable management - not through the owner's
        personal skills, relationships, or presence. Specific actions:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Hire or promote a manager</strong> who can make daily operational decisions without
          you. If the business cannot function for two weeks while you are on vacation, it is too
          owner-dependent to command a premium multiple.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Document all operating procedures</strong> - onboarding, service delivery, vendor
          management, customer communication. Documented processes have transfer value; mental processes
          in the owner's head do not.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Transfer key customer relationships</strong> from the owner to the business entity.
          Introduce customers to your manager, document accounts in your CRM, ensure no customer
          relationship exists primarily as a personal connection that could walk with you.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Reduce your hours credibly and demonstrably.</strong> Track your hours for the
          12 months before listing. Buyers and their diligence advisors will ask to see your calendar.
          A seller who claims "the business runs itself" but is working 60 hours a week will not
          be believed.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>2. Build Recurring Revenue</h2>
      <p>
        Recurring revenue is the most direct path to a premium multiple because it changes the
        nature of the earnings - from transactional (requiring ongoing selling effort) to
        contractual (predictably continuing under any ownership). Industries where this creates
        the largest multiple premium:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Home services:</strong> Annual maintenance contracts, seasonal service agreements,
          priority customer programs. An HVAC company with 60% of revenue from service contracts
          trades significantly above the median compared to one with 100% call-in revenue.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Automotive:</strong> Fleet maintenance contracts with commercial accounts,
          inspection agreements with dealerships. Predictable B2B revenue reduces buyer risk perception.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Personal services:</strong> Membership programs, package deals, retainer-based
          pricing. A hair salon with 200 members paying $79/month has a fundamentally different
          valuation profile than one with 100% walk-in revenue.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Technology and IT services:</strong> Managed services contracts (MSPs) command
          among the highest multiples in the Main Street market because the recurring nature of
          subscription revenue is highly valued by buyers.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Creating recurring revenue takes time to establish credibly - 12–18 months of contract history
        is the minimum that buyers will give meaningful weight. Start building it now.
      </p>

      <h2>3. Diversify Your Customer Base</h2>
      <p>
        The calculator applies −0.25× for concentrated customers (one customer over 40% of revenue)
        and +0.10× for diverse customers (no customer over 15%). The swing is 0.35× - equal to $105,000
        on a $300,000 SDE business at a 3.0× median.
      </p>
      <p>
        The most practical approach depends on your timeline:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>18–24 months before sale:</strong> Actively pursue new customers and accounts,
          even at slightly lower margins, to reduce concentration. Growing total revenue while
          keeping the large customer flat achieves concentration reduction without losing that revenue.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>6–12 months before sale:</strong> Structure your relationship with the concentrated
          customer in a way that reduces perceived transfer risk - multi-year contracts in the business's
          name, documented satisfaction, and ideally a relationship with your manager (not just you).
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Note: customer concentration above 20% requires explicit disclosure in the sale process.
        Attempting to obscure it is both unethical and counterproductive - it will surface in
        diligence and trigger a retrade far more damaging than honest disclosure would have been.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Maximize and Document SDE</h2>
      <p>
        Every legitimate add-back that you fail to document costs you multiple times its face value
        in the sale. A $15,000 vehicle add-back that cannot be supported in diligence is not a
        $15,000 loss - at a 3.0× multiple, it is a $45,000 loss in enterprise value.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two years before your intended sale:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Work with a CPA experienced in business sale preparation to clean up your financial presentation</li>
        <li>Create a detailed add-back schedule for each of the past 3 years, with supporting documentation for each line item</li>
        <li>Ensure personal expenses run through the business are clearly separated from business expenses and documented</li>
        <li>Normalize your financials for any one-time items - document the cause and why they won't recur</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>5. Grow Revenue (While Maintaining Margin)</h2>
      <p>
        Revenue growth of 20%+ per year adds +0.30× to the multiple in the calculator. For a $300,000
        SDE business at a 3.0× median, that is $90,000 in additional valuation. Revenue growth
        signals market momentum - buyers are paying not just for current earnings but for the
        trajectory of future earnings.
      </p>
      <p>
        The critical constraint: margin maintenance. A business growing revenue at 25% annually but
        with declining SDE margins (revenue growing faster than profit) does not benefit from the
        growth multiple - buyers will look at the SDE trend, not the revenue trend. Grow revenue
        with maintained or improving margins to capture the full benefit.
      </p>

      <h2>6. Secure Lease and Physical Infrastructure</h2>
      <p>
        For location-dependent businesses, a secure long-term lease removes a primary deal risk
        and directly supports premium pricing. Before going to market:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Extend your lease to at least 5 years remaining, with a renewal option</li>
        <li>Negotiate a transfer clause that allows lease assignment without landlord veto</li>
        <li>Resolve any deferred maintenance on equipment, facilities, or vehicles</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Equipment deferred maintenance becomes a direct price deduction in buyer negotiations.
        A $20,000 HVAC replacement, a $15,000 lift repair, or a $30,000 roof repair that you know
        is needed - and that the buyer discovers in their inspection - will be deducted from the
        offer price at 100–150% of the actual cost, to account for the buyer's inconvenience.
        Addressing it before listing is almost always the higher-value choice.
      </p>

